{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585258"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:07:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:07:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14944"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14944"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.15,0.38,0.12,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7632"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66432"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7632"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14944"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51883"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"},{"type":"tags","id":"10942"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18669"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18670"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66432"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA bacterial pathogen demonstrates the following characteristics:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHeat-stable enterotoxin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECarbohydrate capsule\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESlime production\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EProtein A on surface\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely bacterial pathogen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Streptococcus pyogenes","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Staphylococcus aureus","Klebsiella pneumoniae","Salmonella typhi"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E uniquely possesses all these virulence factors. Protein A is a surface protein specific to \u003Cem\u003ES. aureus\u003C/em\u003E that binds to immunoglobulin G, helping it evade the immune system. The heat-stable enterotoxin causes food poisoning symptoms, while the carbohydrate capsule provides protection against phagocytosis. Slime production enables biofilm formation and adherence to surfaces.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E produces different toxins (streptolysins) and lacks Protein A\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E has a polysaccharide capsule but lacks Protein A and enterotoxin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EKlebsiella pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E has a prominent capsule but lacks the other characteristic features\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ESalmonella typhi\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E produces endotoxin rather than heat-stable enterotoxin and lacks Protein A\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Staphylococcus aureus is uniquely characterized by the presence of Protein A on its surface, which binds to immunoglobulin G.","Key virulence factors of S. aureus include heat-stable enterotoxin, carbohydrate capsule, and slime production for biofilm formation.","These combined characteristics distinguish S. aureus from other common bacterial pathogens."],"references":[